<font color="#FF0000">TEACHING ABOUT VIET NAM</font><br>
<tt>Wed Mar  5 11:08:29 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Reply to Gerald Ney:<br><br>
Each time I teach my class on violence I ask students the following question, &quot;How many of you have studied violence in high school?&quot; Of the 40 or 50 students in the class, the most hands I ever see is two. Then I ask another question, &quot;Can you name five wars you studied in high school?&quot; They all can name at least 15-20. When I ask if anyone was killed in these wars and if property was destroyed and if killing and destruction is or is not violence, they get very confused and wonder why they never saw the connection between war and violence. Clausewitz and the Sultan are right as far as they go. But as long as we accept them we will live in the world as they define it. A world where war is not violence, it's politics by another means. War is not violence, it's a necessary public spectacle. Is there not another way to define what life is about? I can't remember who said it, I think it was Camus, but as long as we call unpleasant (especially violent) things by names other than what they are, we will be forced to live with them. Only when we call them by their real names will we face the necessity and find the ability to change them.
